{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17530699","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17530699"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T16:09:20+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T16:09:20+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14562"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"14562","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/14562"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.01,0,0.83,0.15,0.01]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7255"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"88257"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"7255","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/7255"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14562"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"72447"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"4"},{"type":"tags","id":"15"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"96"},{"type":"tags","id":"1051"},{"type":"tags","id":"1052"},{"type":"tags","id":"1569"},{"type":"tags","id":"2972"},{"type":"tags","id":"3343"},{"type":"tags","id":"4578"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"17637"},{"type":"contributions","id":"30085"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"88257","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/88257"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 28-year-old woman presents to the Emergency Department with nausea, vomiting, and abdominal pain following a night of heavy alcohol consumption. She appears unwell and confused. Her pulse rate is 120/min, blood pressure 100/60 mmHg, respiratory rate 28/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 37.8\u00b0C. On examination, she has dry mucous membranes. Her past medical history is unknown at the time of presentation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EPoint of care testing reveals blood glucose 28.5 mmol/L (4.0-7.8) and blood ketones 5.8 mmol/L (\u0026lt;0.6). Venous blood gas results reveal:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EpH: 7.21 (7.35-7.45)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EpCO2: 25 mmHg (35-45)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHCO3: 10 mmol/L (22-26)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ELactate: 2.2 mmol/L (0.5-1.6)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ESodium: 132 mmol/L (135-145)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EPotassium: 5.2 mmol/L (3.5-5.0)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EChloride: 95 mmol/L (98-107)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely cause of this patient\u0027s presentation?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Opiate overdose","Airway obstruction","Diabetic ketoacidosis","Lactic acidosis","Diuretic overdose"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient\u0027s presentation is most consistent with \u003Cstrong\u003Ediabetic ketoacidosis (DKA)\u003C/strong\u003E. The key features supporting this diagnosis are marked hyperglycemia (28.5 mmol/L), significantly elevated ketones (5.8 mmol/L), high anion gap metabolic acidosis, and clinical signs of dehydration. An alcohol binge can be a precipitant of DKA in diabetic patients.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOpiate overdose\u003C/strong\u003E typically presents with respiratory depression, pinpoint pupils, and decreased level of consciousness. While this patient is confused, her respiratory rate is not low and her pCO2 is not high, which are inconsistent with opiate toxicity.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAirway obstruction\u003C/strong\u003E would primarily cause respiratory symptoms and hypoxia. This patient\u0027s SpO2 is normal, and her presentation is more consistent with a metabolic rather than respiratory problem.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELactic acidosis\u003C/strong\u003E can occur in various conditions, including shock or severe hypoperfusion. While this patient\u0027s lactate is mildly elevated (2.2 mmol/L), it is not high enough to account for the severity of her acidosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDiuretic overdose\u003C/strong\u003E is less likely to be correct. Excess diuretic intake can cause a metabolic acidosis but typically with a normal anion gap.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIt is important to note that DKA can be the initial presentation of type 1 diabetes, especially in young adults. The history of alcohol consumption may have exacerbated the condition or masked early symptoms. Treatment for DKA involves fluid resuscitation, insulin therapy, and close monitoring of electrolytes, particularly potassium. This patient will require admission for management of DKA and further workup to determine if this is new-onset diabetes or an exacerbation of previously undiagnosed diabetes.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Diabetic ketoacidosis (DKA) is characterised by hyperglycemia, high anion gap metabolic acidosis, and elevated ketones.","Alcohol consumption can precipitate or mask early symptoms of DKA.","Initial emergency workup of suspected DKA must include blood glucose and ketones."],"references":["Lizzo J, Goyal A, Gupta V. Adult Diabetic Ketoacidosis. In: StatPearls [online]. 2023. Available at: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK560723/","Diabetic ketoacidosis. Royal Children\u0027s Hospital, Clinical Practice Guidelines. Updated November 2018. Available from: https://www.rch.org.au/clinicalguide/guideline_index/Diabetic_Ketoacidosis/","Management of diabetic ketoacidosis in adults (age 16 years and over). Queensland Health. Updated November 2023. Available from: https://www.health.qld.gov.au/__data/assets/pdf_file/0019/621640/diabetic-ketoacidosis.pdf"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"72447"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14562"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"72447","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/72447"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-03-02T19:37:38+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-03-02T19:38:21+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7255"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"88257"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"4","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udf6c","name":"Endocrinology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:43+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"15","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/15"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udd54","name":"Nephrology","synonyms":["Renal"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2021-05-21T07:52:08+09:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"24","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/24"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\ude91","name":"Emergency Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"5"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/64"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Diagnos